04931nam a22006735i 9780271087399DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710873997 a10.1515/97802710873992doi  a(DE-B1597)584209  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR830.A42bG66 2020 7aLIT0041602bisacsh04a823/.91093532231 aGonzález, Octavio R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMisfit Modernism :bQueer Forms of Double Exile in the Twentieth-Century Novel /cOctavio R. González. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism ;v3300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: Queer Forms of Double Exile in the Twentieth-Century Novel -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Modernist Misfit: Antisocial and Intersectional -- t1. Methodology Immanent Reading -- t2. Narrating the Psychology of a "Despised Mulatto" in Larsen's Quicksand -- t3. Affective Realism Feeling Like a "Total Misfit" in Thurman's The Blacker the Berry -- t4. Narrating the Mood of the Underdog in Rhys's Quartet -- t5. Isherwood's Impersonality "Nonconformist" Queer Relationality in A Single Man -- tCoda: Two Forms of Feeling Like a Misfit -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book, Octavio R. González revisits the theme of alienation in the twentieth-century novel, identifying an alternative aesthetic centered on the experience of double exile, or marginalization from both majority and home culture. This misfit modernist aesthetic decenters the mainstream narrative of modernism-which explores alienation from a universal and existential perspective-by showing how a group of authors leveraged modernist narrative to explore minoritarian experiences of cultural nonbelonging.Tying the biography of a particular author to a close reading of one of that author's major works, González considers in turn Nella Larsen's Quicksand, Wallace Thurman's The Blacker the Berry, Jean Rhys's Quartet, and Christopher Isherwood's A Single Man. Each of these novels explores conditions of maladjustment within one of three burgeoning cultural movements that sought representation in the greater public sphere: the New Negro movement during the Harlem Renaissance, the 1920s Paris expatriate scene, and the queer expatriate scene in Los Angeles before Stonewall. Using a methodological approach that resists institutional taxonomies of knowledge, González shows that this double exile speaks profoundly through largely autobiographical narratives and that the novels' protagonists challenge the compromises made by these minoritarian groups out of an urge to assimilate into dominant social norms and values.Original and innovative, Misfit Modernism is a vital contribution to conversations about modernism in the contexts of sexual identity, nationality, and race. Moving beyond the debates over the intellectual legacies of intersectionality and queer theory, González shows us new ways to think about exclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAlienation (Social psychology) in literature. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature). 0aQueer theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271087399zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271087399423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271087399.jpg